and now the files tested on equivalence:

* File `/work/bitcoin/bitcoin/ci/scratch/test_runner/test_runner_â¿_ð_20210122_135553/wallet_hd_193/node1/regtest/wallets` doe/wallet.dat` does exist.
* File `/work/bitcoin/bitcoin/ci/scratch/test_runner/test_runner_â¿_ð_20210122_135553/wallet_hd_193/node1/hd.bak` does NOT exist.

And now why do we get that `filesystem error: in equivalent: Operation not supported`?

I have put together two samples for `fs::equivalent`:

```cpp
// Run with: g++ --std=c++17 equivalent.cpp17.cpp && ./a.out

#include <string>
#include <iostream>
#include <filesystem>
namespace fs = std::filesystem;

int main()
{
    fs::path pathSrc = "/home/user/a.log";
    fs::path pathDest = "/home/user/b.log";
    bool success = fs::equivalent(pathSrc, pathDest);

    std::cout << "Result is: " << (int)success << "\n";

    // # Case "Both files do not exist"
    // 
    // Exception is thrown:
    // 
    // > terminate called after throwing an instance of 'std::filesystem::__cxx11::filesystem_error'
    // > what():  filesystem error: cannot check file equivalence: No such file or directory [/home/user/a.log] [/home/user/b.log]
    // > Aborted (core dumped)

    // # Case "pathSrc exists, pathDest does not"
    //
    // No exception. Std output is:
    // > Result is: 0

    // # Case "Both pathSrc and pathDest exist but are different."
    //
    // No exception. Std output is:
    // > Result is: 0    

    // # Case "Both pathSrc and pathDest exist and b.log is symlink for a.log." (`ln -s a.log b.log`)
    //
    // No exception. Std output is:
    // > Result is: 0    
}
```

and Boost variant:

```cpp
// Run with: g++ equivalent.boost.cpp -lboost_system -lboost_filesystem && ./a.out

#include <string>
#include <iostream>
#include <boost/filesystem.hpp>
#include <boost/filesystem/fstream.hpp>
namespace fs = boost::filesystem;

int main()
{
    fs::path pathSrc = "/home/user/a.log";
    fs::path pathDest = "/home/user/b.log";
    bool success = fs::equivalent(pathSrc, pathDest);

    std::cout << "Result is: " << (int)success << "\n";

    // # Case "Both files do not exist"
    //
    // Exception is thrown:
    // 
    // terminate called after throwing an instance of 'boost::filesystem::filesystem_error'
    //  what():  boost::filesystem::equivalent: Operation not permitted: "/home/user/a.log", "/home/user/b.log"
    // Aborted (core dumped)

    // # Case "pathSrc exists, pathDest does not"
    //
    // No exception. Std output is:
    // > Result is: 0

    // # Case "Both pathSrc and pathDest exist but are different."
    //
    // No exception. Std output is:
    // > Result is: 0    

    // # Case "Both pathSrc and pathDest exist and b.log is symlink for a.log." (`ln -s a.log b.log`)
    //
    // No exception. Std output is:
    // > Result is: 0    
}
```
So these samples shows that `fs::equivalent` behaves similarly in both implementations when compiled using `g++`.

And now finally, when I run the sample in Docker:

```
clang++ -stdlib=libc++ --std=c++17 equivalent.cpp17.cpp && ./a.out  # /home/user/a.log EXISTS!

// returns:
// > terminating with uncaught exception of type std::__1::__fs::filesystem::filesystem_error: filesystem error: in equivalent: Operation not supported [/home/user/a.log] [/home/user/b.log]
// > Aborted (core dumped)

clang++ --std=c++17 equivalent.cpp17.cpp && ./a.out 
// returns:
// > Result is: 0
```

So it looks like `-stdlib=libc++` is the culprit or am I missing something? Can anybody verify?

